# Interfaces and Type Aliases

TypeScript has two ways to name a shape: `interface` and `type`. They look almost identical at first glance. The key mental model: **`interface` is an open contract that can be extended and merged later. `type` is a closed, one-shot label that can express anything an interface can't.**

```
  interface User           type User =
  ┌──────────────┐        ┌──────────────┐
  │ name: string │   vs   │ name: string │
  │ age: number  │        │ age: number  │
  └──────────────┘        └──────────────┘
       ▲ open                  ▲ closed
  can be extended          can be unioned
  can be merged            can be intersected
  class can implement      can alias primitives
```

## Structural Typing — shapes, not names

TypeScript uses **structural typing**: a value is compatible with a type if it has at least the required shape. The name doesn't matter.

```ts
interface Point { x: number; y: number; }

function draw(p: Point) {
  console.log(p.x, p.y);
}

// This object has no 'Point' annotation — but it satisfies the shape
const pt = { x: 10, y: 20, label: 'origin' };
draw(pt);  // ✓ — extra property 'label' is fine when passing via variable

// Direct object literal DOES trigger excess property checks:
draw({ x: 10, y: 20, label: 'origin' });  // ✗ Error — excess property in literal
```

```
Structural check mental model:

  Required: { x: number; y: number }
  Provided: { x: number; y: number; label: string }

  Does provided have ALL required fields with correct types?
  Yes → compatible ✓

  Excess property check only applies to FRESH object literals
  passed directly to a typed parameter.
```

## interface — the open contract

```ts
// Basic declaration
interface Animal {
  name: string;
  sound(): string;
}

// Extension — just like class inheritance
interface Dog extends Animal {
  breed: string;
}

// Multiple extension
interface ServiceDog extends Dog, Trainable {
  handler: string;
}

// Classes implement interfaces
class Labrador implements Dog {
  name = 'Rex';
  breed = 'Labrador';
  sound() { return 'woof'; }
}
```

### Declaration Merging — interfaces can grow

If you declare the same interface twice, TypeScript **merges** them. This is how `lib.dom.d.ts` and third-party library augmentations work.

```ts
interface Window {
  myAppVersion: string;   // augment the global Window type
}

// Now window.myAppVersion is typed — no error
window.myAppVersion = '1.0.0';

// Same-name declarations merge:
interface Config { host: string; }
interface Config { port: number; }
// Result: Config = { host: string; port: number; }
```

## type alias — the flexible label

```ts
// Alias a primitive
type UserId = string;
type Milliseconds = number;

// Union — only possible with type
type StringOrNumber = string | number;
type Status = 'idle' | 'loading' | 'success' | 'error';

// Intersection — combine shapes
type AdminUser = User & { role: 'admin' };

// Tuple
type Pair<T> = [T, T];

// Function signature
type Callback = (err: Error | null, data: string) => void;

// Mapped type (impossible with interface)
type Readonly<T> = { readonly [K in keyof T]: T[K] };

// Conditional type (impossible with interface)
type IsString<T> = T extends string ? true : false;
```

## interface vs type — the decision table

```
┌──────────────────────────────┬───────────┬───────────┐
│ Feature                      │ interface │   type    │
├──────────────────────────────┼───────────┼───────────┤
│ Describe object shape        │    ✓      │     ✓     │
│ Class implements             │    ✓      │     ✓     │
│ Extends / inheritance        │    ✓      │  via &    │
│ Declaration merging          │    ✓      │     ✗     │
│ Union types  A | B           │    ✗      │     ✓     │
│ Intersection A & B           │  extends  │     ✓     │
│ Alias primitives             │    ✗      │     ✓     │
│ Tuple types                  │    ✗      │     ✓     │
│ Mapped types                 │    ✗      │     ✓     │
│ Conditional types            │    ✗      │     ✓     │
│ Recursive self-reference     │    ✓      │     ✓     │
│ Error messages — cleaner     │    ✓      │  varies   │
└──────────────────────────────┴───────────┴───────────┘

Rule of thumb:
  Object shapes → interface (benefits from merging, extends, implements)
  Everything else → type (unions, tuples, mapped, conditional)
```

## Optional, Readonly, and Index Signatures

```ts
interface Config {
  readonly host: string;        // cannot reassign after creation
  port?: number;                // optional — may be undefined
  [key: string]: unknown;       // index signature — any extra string key
}

const cfg: Config = { host: 'localhost' };
cfg.host = '127.0.0.1';  // ✗ Error — readonly
cfg.port = 3000;          // ✓ — optional but valid
cfg.debug = true;         // ✓ — index signature allows this
```

## Discriminated Unions (tagged unions)

A pattern where a shared literal field tells TypeScript which variant is active:

```ts
type Shape =
  | { kind: 'circle';    radius: number }
  | { kind: 'square';    side: number   }
  | { kind: 'rectangle'; w: number; h: number };

function area(s: Shape): number {
  switch (s.kind) {
    case 'circle':    return Math.PI * s.radius ** 2;
    case 'square':    return s.side ** 2;
    case 'rectangle': return s.w * s.h;
    // TypeScript knows s is never here — exhaustive
  }
}
```

```
Discriminated union mental model:

Shape
  │
  ├── kind: 'circle'    → unlocks .radius
  ├── kind: 'square'    → unlocks .side
  └── kind: 'rectangle' → unlocks .w, .h

The 'kind' tag is a TYPE NARROWING KEY.
Each case == a different shape with different props.
```

## Common Pitfalls
- Using `interface` for union types — interfaces can't express `A | B`
- Forgetting excess property checks only apply to fresh literals (not variables)
- Declaration merging surprises: adding a field to a global interface (`Window`, `Array`) changes it everywhere
- Using `type` for object shapes in libraries that need augmentation — consumers can't merge your `type`
- Confusing structural compatibility with nominal equality — TypeScript doesn't care about class names, only shapes

